6 — Dashboards — layout & metrics (wireframe-style descriptions)

Student dashboard (two-column)

Left column (main): “Continue learning” card (big), list of enrolled courses (cards w/ progress) Right column (sidebar): calendar (deadlines), upcoming events, notifications summary, quick links

Essential metrics

courses enrolled

Avg progress %

Assignments due this week

Recent grades


Teacher dashboard

Top: course-level cards (students | avg progress | pending grading) Mid: quick actions (create lesson, grade assignments) Right: analytics sparkline (enrollment trend), notifications

Key teacher metrics

Pending grading count

Completion rate per course

Active students (last 7 days)


Admin dashboard

Grid of widgets: users, active sessions, courses pending approval, storage used, reports.


---

7 — UI / Layout & design system

Layout: responsive grid, mobile-first. Use a topbar with brand + global search + profile menu; for desktop, enable a left sidebar inside dashboards.

Cards: modular, consistent spacing, subtle shadows.

Spacing & grid: 8px baseline grid.

Color system: 1 primary color, 1 accent, neutral greys, 1 success color, 1 danger color. Use CSS variables for theme.

Typography: Clear hierarchy — large readable headings, 16px base body. Use system fonts or a web font with fallback.

Icons: Use SVG icons (inline SVG for animation control).

Imagery: course thumbnails, teacher avatars.

Dark mode: optional — design tokens make this easy.



---

8 — Animations & microinteractions (what to use & where)

Microinteractions

Button hover (slight scale up or underline sweep)

Input focus (border glow + label float)

Toasts slide from corner with small fade

Form submit success checkmark animation (SVG morph)


Page transitions

Smooth fade/slide between dashboard sub-pages (avoid heavy motion)


Progress UI

Animated progress bars when loading/advancing lesson


Lesson interactions

Accordion expand/collapse with height transition for modules

Skeleton loaders for lesson content while fetching


Accessibility tip: provide a "reduce motion" preference respect media-query.


Keep animations subtle (100–300ms) and purposeful.


---

9 — UX patterns & accessibility

Use semantic HTML (nav, header, main, article, aside, footer)

Keyboard navigable (tab order, skip to content)

Visible focus states

ARIA where dynamic content is used (modals, live regions)

Color contrast >= WCAG AA for text

Provide transcripts for videos and alt for images

Form validation: inline messages + summary on top for screen readers

Mobile-first breakpoints and touch targets >= 44px



---

10 — Data model (conceptual entities & relationships)

User (id, name, email, role, profile)

Course (id, title, description, category, teacher_id, thumbnail)

Module (id, course_id, title, order)

Lesson (id, module_id, title, content, resources, order)

Enrollment (user_id, course_id, enrolled_at, progress)

Assignment (id, lesson_id/course_id, description, due_date)

Submission (id, assignment_id, user_id, file_url, grade, feedback)

Quiz (id, course_id, questions)

Question (id, quiz_id, type, content, choices)

Result (user_id, quiz_id, score, attempts)

Message / Thread (participants, messages)

Notification Relationships: Course ↔ Modules ↔ Lessons; User ↔ Enrollment ↔ Course; Teacher ↔ Course.



---

11 — Client-side behaviours & state ideas

State management: small app: use modular JS with local modules; for session-like state use sessionStorage and for caching use localStorage.

Forms: client-side validation + server-side (simulate server with JSON files for demo).

Routing: use simple hash-based routing for SPA-like feel (optional).

Persistence for demo: store mock courses and enrollments in local JSON or localStorage for offline demo.



---

12 — Security & privacy (must-haves)

Don’t store passwords in plain text (for real apps — hash & salt).

Implement CSRF protections (if building real back-end).

Validate inputs on client and server to prevent XSS/SQL injection.

File upload size/type limits, virus scanning (conceptually).

Privacy: show minimal personal data, provide terms & privacy page.


(You’re doing only front-end now but mention these.)


---

13 — Performance & SEO basics

Use lazy loading for lesson images/videos.

Minimize JS bundle size: modular code, avoid huge libs.

Use semantic markup and meta tags for SEO: title, description, og tags.

Optimize images (webp), compress assets, use caching headers.

Accessibility and semantic markup help SEO.



---

14 — Testing & QA (what to check)

Responsive checks at common widths (320, 375, 768, 1024, 1440)

Forms: validation, error messages, edge cases

File uploads: size/type tests

Authentication flows: signup/login/forgot password

Quiz edge-cases: timer expiry, save-progress

Accessibility quick audit (axe or Lighthouse)

Cross-browser basic compatibility (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, mobile)



---

15 — Deployment & demo strategy

For a school project demo, you can deploy static build to GitHub Pages, Netlify, or Vercel.

If using dynamic behavior (mock server), host JSON files or use Netlify functions / simple JSON server.

Prepare a short demo script: register → enroll → go through a lesson → submit assignment → teacher grade.



